<item>
 <title>K Cups Have Taken Over  </title>
 <link>http://www.completelyeco.com/articles/k-cups-have-taken-over</link>
 <description>
&lt;div class=&quot;serif field field-name-body field-type-text-with-summary field-label-hidden clearfix&quot;&gt;
  
  &lt;!-- THIS SHOULD BE FOR JUST THE BODY --&gt;
  
  &lt;div class=&quot;field-items&quot;&gt;
          &lt;div class=&quot;field-item even&quot;&gt;&lt;p&gt;I pose to you this: We have been given these beautiful, high tech, “efficient”, one cup coffee makers. But efficient, how can we call them efficient when they create nothing but plastic waste? Each individual K Cup I try is delicious and I have even gone as far as using “&lt;a href=&quot;http://www.amazon.com/gp/product/B003DBJ3SI/ref=as_li_ss_tl?ie=UTF8&amp;amp;tag=completelyeco-20&amp;amp;linkCode=as2&amp;amp;camp=217145&amp;amp;creative=399373&amp;amp;creativeASIN=B003DBJ3SI&quot;&gt;my favorite&lt;/a&gt;” at least once a day. That means I am throwing away roughly a cubic inch of plastic 265 times a year. Why can’t we create K Cups that you can recycle? &lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;I vow to try making my one cup of coffee from now on with the reusable K Cup that originally came with the machine.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;/div&gt;
      &lt;/div&gt;
&lt;/div&gt;

